---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const title = "True Residential Refrigerator Repair Los Angeles";
const description = "True Residential refrigerator repair in LA — column, glass-door, undercounter, Pro Series. Middleby sub-brand pro-grade residential. $89 diagnostic waived. (424) 325-0520.";
const canonical = "https://samedayappliance.repair/brands/true-residential-refrigerator-repair/";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Is True Residential the same company as True Manufacturing's commercial refrigerators?",
    a: "Same roots, different companies now. True Manufacturing — the O'Fallon, Missouri company that's made commercial reach-in refrigerators since 1945 — is the parent that launched True Residential as a separate division in 2006 to bring pro-grade refrigeration to residential kitchens. In 2015 Middleby Corporation acquired the residential business. Today True Residential is a Middleby sub-brand; True Manufacturing (commercial) remains a separate company. Parts, service channels, and even internal build details are not interchangeable — a True Residential column and a True commercial reach-in share aesthetic DNA but are different refrigeration platforms. Our team services both, but on separate service scopes. Commercial side lives on our <a href='/brands/commercial-refrigeration/true-refrigeration-commercial-repair/'>True commercial refrigeration repair</a> page."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the difference between True Residential's column fridges and other luxury columns like Sub-Zero or Liebherr?",
    a: "True Residential built its identity on commercial-grade refrigeration architecture adapted to residential cabinetry — heavier-gauge stainless, commercial-style forced-air circulation, and cooling coil configurations borrowed from their commercial reach-in lineage. Sub-Zero is residential-designed from the ground up with dual-refrigeration architecture and Wisconsin family-owned heritage. Liebherr is European architect-modernist with BioFresh humidity control. True Residential's pitch: you're getting commercial reliability in a residential form factor. In practice, all three are excellent at their spec and pick differences come down to aesthetic (True Residential's stainless reads more commercial-industrial, Sub-Zero reads American-luxury, Liebherr reads European-modernist), price point, and dealer availability. Our field data: all three run long service lives; True Residential's commercial-derived components are genuinely robust."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you service glass-door residential refrigerators — the True Residential merchandiser-style units?",
    a: "Yes. The glass-door True Residential refrigerator — usually installed in an entertaining space, a butler's pantry, a home bar, a pool cabana — uses essentially the same commercial-derived forced-air refrigeration as the solid-door column, with the addition of heated-glass door construction to prevent condensation. LA humidity affects glass-door units more than solid-door in Malibu, Pacific Palisades coastal, and poolside installations. Service scope on glass-door: door-heater element (prevents interior condensation), perimeter gasket, door-hinge torque (glass doors are heavier than solid), and the refrigeration cycle. Field installation note: we install extra door-heater load on coastal units because ocean humidity overwhelms the standard-spec heater on older SKUs. Common repair bands similar to solid-door with $80–$150 added for door-heater work."
  },
  {
    q: "Can you service True Residential undercounter refrigerators installed in outdoor kitchens?",
    a: "Undercounter True Residential units destined for outdoor kitchen installation are typically the outdoor-rated SKU line (our separate <a href='/brands/true-residential-outdoor-refrigerator-repair/'>outdoor refrigerator page</a> goes deeper on that scope). Undercounter units installed indoors — a wet bar, a butler's pantry, a kitchen-island drawer — are covered on this page. Common service on indoor undercounter: door-gasket replacement, condenser fan motor, evaporator defrost, compressor. Build tolerance on undercounter True is tighter than generic undercounter fridges — the commercial-architecture compressor runs slightly louder than a typical residential unit, which sometimes surprises homeowners; it's a spec choice, not a failure. On install we occasionally shim the compressor isolation mounts if the noise is radiating into cabinetry; that's a 45-minute adjustment, not a warranty fix."
  },
  {
    q: "How does the commercial-grade compressor in True Residential affect service life?",
    a: "Commercial-architecture compressors in True Residential column fridges are sized and duty-cycled for commercial use — they're specified heavier than typical residential compressors. In residential use that commercial spec translates into long service life: 12 to 16 years as a realistic field range before a major compressor-side service decision, compared to 10 to 12 years typical for residential-only architectures. The trade-off is slightly higher noise floor (commercial compressors run louder than purpose-built residential units) and slightly higher power draw. We've opened True Residential column fridges installed 2010–2012 that are still running on original compressors; the refrigeration side is genuinely long-lived. Refrigerant circuit serviceability is also slightly better — the copper tubing and connection points are commercial-spec, making field repair of a refrigerant-side fault easier than on some residential-compressor architectures."
  },
  {
    q: "Who installs True Residential in LA and who services them?",
    a: "True Residential sells through authorized dealers — not big-box retail. LA coverage is handled through a handful of luxury-appliance showrooms primarily on the Westside; install is usually coordinated by the dealer's preferred installer at time of project. For service after the install, True Residential warranty work within the first year is handled by the factory-authorized network. After warranty, households typically call either the dealer's preferred service company or an independent luxury-refrigeration specialist. Our team is regular visitors to Beverly Hills, Bel Air, Pacific Palisades, Malibu, and Newport Coast on True Residential service — the units are scattered through high-end installs where the homeowner or designer specifically wanted the commercial-grade option. Parts come through Middleby's residential parts channel, typically 3–5 business days to LA on factory-exact items."
  },
  {
    q: "What does True Residential refrigerator repair typically cost in LA?",
    a: "Our residential diagnostic is $89, waived when you authorize the repair. Common True Residential refrigerator bands: door gasket (column, solid-door) $240–$420 installed; door gasket (glass-door) $280–$460; door-heater element $220–$380; condenser fan motor $280–$480; evaporator fan $260–$440; evaporator defrost heater $320–$540; control-board replacement $480–$780; compressor swap (commercial-spec, residential SKU) $1,200–$2,200 depending on refrigerant and tonnage; ice-maker fill-valve and descaling $280–$420. Glass-door units add $80–$150 for door-heater work. Undercounter repair scopes land on the lower end of each range because the hardware is smaller. If a unit is 15-plus years old and a compressor-side fault surfaces, we walk through repair-vs-replace math before quoting the large job — the commercial-grade compressor cost isn't trivial and needs to pencil against replacement."
  }
];

