        kitchens (Bel Air, Pacific Palisades, Hollywood Hills), glass-door residential merchandiser-style in
        entertaining spaces and pool cabanas across Malibu and Newport, undercounter units in wet bars and
        butler's pantries throughout the Westside. The failure pattern reflects the commercial lineage: we see fewer
        compressor-side failures than mainstream residential brands and more door-hardware + door-heater calls on
        glass-door SKUs in coastal-humidity installs. Scope honesty up front: beer-dispenser and outdoor refrigerator
        service have their own dedicated combo pages — see the links in the hero.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>True Residential refrigerator failures we see most often in LA kitchens</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Pattern recognition from running column, glass-door, and undercounter service across LA. These six failure
        clusters cover the bulk of our dispatch.
      </p>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Glass-door heater failure on coastal-humidity units</h3>
        <p>
          Glass-door True Residential units in Malibu, Pacific Palisades pool-cabana installs, and Newport Coast
          accumulate interior condensation on the glass when the perimeter door heater fails. Heater element is a
          resistance wire embedded in the door frame; in heavy ocean-humidity exposure the element runs harder than
          spec and fails earlier than in drier installs. Typical service: meter element for continuity, swap if open
          circuit, verify the heater runs at nameplate amps before leaving. On older SKUs installed 2008–2014 we
          occasionally add a secondary heater-load upgrade because the factory-spec heater was undersized for coastal
          exposure. Standard element swap $220–$380; coastal-upgrade add $80–$150.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Commercial-spec door gasket wear — column doors take heavy sealing load</h3>
        <p>
          Column-door gaskets on True Residential carry commercial-grade sealing load on a residential duty cycle.
          They wear slightly differently than residential-only gaskets — usually compression loss on the hinge side
          first, creating a small cold-air leak that shows as frost creeping down the door frame. Our techs identify
          the failure by running a dollar-bill pull test on the seal at 6 points around the door perimeter. Gasket
          swap on a column door is 90 minutes and the hinge alignment gets verified as part of the work. Two-hour
          job when the gasket is in the common True Residential profiles we stock on the truck.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Condenser fan motor failure — commercial-sized motors outlast the rest, then fail</h3>
        <p>
          Commercial-spec condenser fan motors in True Residential run in the 12-to-16-year life band — longer than
          mainstream residential. When they finally fail it's usually all at once: noisy operation for a few days,
          then motor stops. On a True column the compressor protects itself on high-head safety and shuts down; on a
          glass-door merchandiser-style the condenser fan failure surfaces as the unit running warm overall. Fan
          motor swap from True Residential parts stock (3-5 days to LA) or occasionally a compatible commercial-grade
          replacement if the customer needs it on site within 24 hours. $280–$480 installed depending on motor size.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Ice-maker hard-water failure on combination SKUs</h3>
        <p>
          True Residential combination column and glass-door units with integrated ice-maker accumulate mineral scale
          in the fill valve and ice mold, worst in Encino, Sherman Oaks, Tarzana, Calabasas, Pasadena — LA's harder-
          water neighborhoods. Ice production drops from full bin to half to occasional over 6–12 months. Descaling
          cycle plus fill-valve replacement resolves it in one visit. On heavy-ice-production households we recommend
          annual descaling as preventive maintenance. Standard descale + fill-valve service $280–$420.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Undercounter compressor noise floor — spec, not failure</h3>
        <p>
          The most common "my True Residential is making noise" call we run is actually not a failure — it's the
          commercial-compressor noise floor on undercounter units being louder than the customer expected. If the
          homeowner moved from a quiet residential undercounter and replaced with True Residential, the noise
          difference can be 3-5 dB at the cabinet face. Our techs shim the compressor isolation mounts to reduce
          radiated noise into adjacent cabinetry — that's a 45-minute adjustment that usually drops perceived noise
          to the "acceptable" threshold. We're upfront about this: it's a spec characteristic of commercial
          architecture, not a fix. If the noise is unacceptable after isolation tuning, the fridge is working as
          designed and the complaint is a spec-vs-expectation mismatch.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Evaporator defrost heater failure on column freezers</h3>
        <p>
          Column freezer units — separate TUR/TUF freezer column, or the freezer section of a combination column —
          run a defrost cycle on a timer or demand control. When defrost stops completing, ice builds on the coil,
          airflow chokes, and the freezer drifts warm even with the compressor running hard. Usual failure points:
          defrost termination thermostat, defrost heater element, or defrost timer. Our techs check in that order;
          ice-cleanup on the coil uses a steam kettle (never a chisel — aluminum coils puncture easily and the
          repair tripled in cost). Standard defrost-side service $320–$540 depending on which component failed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

