  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>True Residential vs Sub-Zero vs Liebherr — how our techs think about the column landscape</h2>
      <p>
        Three brands dominate the luxury residential column segment in LA: Sub-Zero, Liebherr, and True Residential.
        (Miele MasterCool is a close fourth on modernist projects.) Each has a distinct architectural approach and
        a distinct buyer profile. Customers sometimes call us before they buy asking which to pick; we don't sell
        appliances so we don't have a commercial stake, but the field pattern is worth stating straight.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>Sub-Zero</b> is the incumbent luxury spec in LA — Wisconsin family-owned (Bakke family, since 1945),
        dual-refrigeration residential architecture, best parts availability (same-day or next-day most LA
        neighborhoods). See <a href="/brands/sub-zero-refrigerator-repair/">Sub-Zero refrigerator repair</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>Liebherr</b> is the European modernist alternative — Austrian-German family-owned (Hans Liebherr, since
        1949), BioFresh humidity-controlled drawers, tighter integrated-install tolerances. See
        <a href="/brands/liebherr-refrigerator-repair/">Liebherr refrigerator repair</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>True Residential</b> is the commercial-architecture-in-residential-form alternative. Middleby sub-brand
        since 2015, commercial-grade components adapted to residential cabinetry, heaviest-gauge stainless of the
        three, longest realistic compressor life (12–16 years). Aesthetic reads more commercial-industrial than
        Sub-Zero or Liebherr — some owners specifically want that look; others would read it as wrong for their
        kitchen. Picked by homeowners who want the commercial reliability story and who appreciate the stainless
        pro-grade aesthetic.
      </p>
      <p>
        None of the three is objectively "better." True Residential wins on compressor-side service life,
        Sub-Zero wins on parts availability, Liebherr wins on tightest integrated-install tolerances. Our team
        services all three equally.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

